<DocsLayout
  title="Memory & embeddings"
  eyebrow="Architecture"
  description="Local memories, provider-neutral embeddings, and retrieval configuration."
  prev={{ href: "/docs/providers/", title: "Inference providers" }}
  next={{ href: "/docs/openrouter/", title: "OpenRouter" }}
>
  <p>
    Roder stores project and global memories through <code>roder-ext-memory</code>. The
    default store is SQLite under Roder home, exposed through CLI commands, app-server
    methods, and model-facing memory tools instead of direct database access.
  </p>

  <h2>Scopes</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><code>project</code> memories are resolved from the active workspace.</li>
    <li><code>global</code> memories are user-wide and can be included with project queries.</li>
    <li><code>workspace</code> and <code>thread</code> scopes remain available for extension authors.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>CLI</h2>
  <pre><code>roder memory list --scope project
roder memory query "release process" --scope project --include-global
roder memory save "use cargo nextest for this repo" --scope project
roder memory providers list
roder memory providers set google --model gemini-embedding-2
roder memory providers set zeroentropy --model zembed-1</code></pre>

  <h2>Embedding providers</h2>
  <p>
    Embeddings use the provider-neutral <code>EmbeddingProvider</code> contract. First-party
    remote providers are OpenAI <code>text-embedding-3-large</code>, Google
    <code>gemini-embedding-2</code>, and ZeroEntropy <code>zembed-1</code>. Query and document
    intent is part of the shared request, so providers can use retrieval-specific prompt
    or API fields while the memory store stays provider-neutral.
  </p>

  <pre><code>{`[memories]
embedding_provider = "zeroentropy"
embedding_model = "zembed-1"

[embedding_providers.zeroentropy]
enabled = true
api_key_env = "ZEROENTROPY_API_KEY"
endpoint = "https://api.zeroentropy.dev/v1"
dimensions = 2560`}</code></pre>

  <p>
    Google embeddings resolve Gemini or Google AI API-key environment variables. ZeroEntropy
    resolves <code>RODER_ZEROENTROPY_API_KEY</code> or <code>ZEROENTROPY_API_KEY</code> and can
    use the EU endpoint when configured. Selecting a remote embedding provider sends
    memory text to that provider; use a local command-backed provider or local extension
    when memory text must stay fully local.
  </p>

  <h2>App-server methods</h2>
  <p>
    Clients use <code>memory/list</code>, <code>memory/read</code>, <code>memory/save</code>,
    <code>memory/update</code>, <code>memory/delete</code>, <code>memory/query</code>,
    <code>memory/provider/list</code>, <code>memory/provider/set</code>, and
    <code>memory/recall/preview</code>. Provider changes emit
    <code>memory/providerChanged</code>; memory CRUD and recall emit their own stream events
    for clients that render memory activity.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
